00:05:00.950 --> 00:05:03.910
So what shaped your interest
in doing a TV project?

00:05:03.910 --> 00:05:07.562
I know you started a lot in
film, what attracted you to TV?

00:05:07.562 --> 00:05:09.020
WILL PACKER: I love
TV because it's

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:11.146
a different connection
with audiences

00:05:11.146 --> 00:05:12.270
that you're able to foster.

00:05:12.270 --> 00:05:15.490
So with the feature film-- even
the greatest feature film--

00:05:15.490 --> 00:05:17.340
you go in and it's
an hour and a half,

00:05:17.340 --> 00:05:19.180
two hour, two
hour-plus experience,

00:05:19.180 --> 00:05:21.537
and for the most part,
it can stay with you

00:05:21.537 --> 00:05:23.120
but when you leave
the theater, you've

00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:25.170
left that film in the theater.

00:05:25.170 --> 00:05:27.990
And until you do
another version of it,

00:05:27.990 --> 00:05:30.120
you do a sequel
or you revisit it,

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:31.750
for the most part
that content is

00:05:31.750 --> 00:05:35.100
meant to be encapsulated in
that period of time and be over.

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:38.280
Whereas with television,
you are intended

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:40.340
to invest in these characters
over the long term,

00:05:40.340 --> 00:05:41.173
I really liked that.

00:05:41.173 --> 00:05:43.370
As a creative filmmaker,
I liked the idea

00:05:43.370 --> 00:05:45.900
of being a part of a process
that creates characters

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:49.360
that allows viewers to take the
journey over and over again.

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:52.930
So obviously the television
landscape is changing rapidly

00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:55.330
now and the way people consume
television is changing,

00:05:55.330 --> 00:05:58.370
but people still look for
that organic investment

00:05:58.370 --> 00:06:01.010
with real characters,
people that they can really

00:06:01.010 --> 00:06:03.490
get to know and really
get invested in.

00:06:03.490 --> 00:06:05.410
MARJAI ROBERTS:
Agreed, definitely.

