00:16:56.360 --> 00:16:58.490
MARJAI ROBERTS:
Yeah, it's not good.

00:16:58.490 --> 00:16:59.090
Definitely.

00:16:59.090 --> 00:17:06.720
So we hear a lot of dialogue in
the news and in our community

00:17:06.720 --> 00:17:10.560
that diversity and actors,
and seeing people, diversity,

00:17:10.560 --> 00:17:16.550
on TV, is really important
in our community today.

00:17:16.550 --> 00:17:19.470
And I think we
forget a lot of times

00:17:19.470 --> 00:17:22.700
that the people in the
background, it's just

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:27.310
is important for them to be
diverse as well because they

00:17:27.310 --> 00:17:28.760
are the decision makers.

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:31.580
So how does that impact you?

00:17:31.580 --> 00:17:35.150
Do you agree or do
you think that's fair

00:17:35.150 --> 00:17:38.190
that it's really important to
have that diversity in sitting

00:17:38.190 --> 00:17:38.760
at the table?

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:39.510
WILL PACKER: Yeah.

00:17:39.510 --> 00:17:42.390
First of all, diversity
is important for a couple

00:17:42.390 --> 00:17:43.110
of reasons.

00:17:43.110 --> 00:17:46.610
Not only because
it's the right thing

00:17:46.610 --> 00:17:51.370
to do, just to be upfront
and blatant about it,

00:17:51.370 --> 00:17:54.620
but also because it makes
good business sense.

00:17:54.620 --> 00:17:56.790
That's what America
looks like now.

00:17:56.790 --> 00:17:59.530
It does not look like
just one monolithic group,

00:17:59.530 --> 00:18:03.230
America looks like how
the world looks, diverse.

00:18:03.230 --> 00:18:06.690
And various races, ethnicities,
and cultural backgrounds,

00:18:06.690 --> 00:18:08.310
and sexual orientations.

00:18:08.310 --> 00:18:10.300
So if you're going
to make content

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:12.340
for the broadest
possible audience,

00:18:12.340 --> 00:18:14.170
you need to represent
that audience.

00:18:14.170 --> 00:18:15.920
So that's something
that's very important.

00:18:15.920 --> 00:18:18.336
When you talk about behind the
scenes, people like myself,

00:18:18.336 --> 00:18:18.990
you're right.

00:18:18.990 --> 00:18:21.980
Obviously, I'm going to have a
different level of sensitivity

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:25.320
about diversity, perhaps, than
some of my white counterparts.

00:18:25.320 --> 00:18:28.140
Doesn't mean that we both
can't push it in the same way,

00:18:28.140 --> 00:18:30.790
but it is important to
have diversity in front,

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:33.290
and behind, the camera
because it informs

00:18:33.290 --> 00:18:34.510
the decisions that you make.

00:18:34.510 --> 00:18:37.730
And so in order to have great
shows that are organically

00:18:37.730 --> 00:18:42.150
diverse-- again, not just,
let's cast a person of color

00:18:42.150 --> 00:18:44.155
because we need to
meet some quota,

00:18:44.155 --> 00:18:46.270
but actual themes
and subject matters

00:18:46.270 --> 00:18:50.130
that are organic to
a diverse cast-- then

00:18:50.130 --> 00:18:52.640
you have to have people
that really understand

00:18:52.640 --> 00:18:54.170
and have a perspective.

00:18:54.170 --> 00:18:56.030
It also makes the
content better.

00:18:56.030 --> 00:19:00.740
Because if you and I like
something, it could be good,

00:19:00.740 --> 00:19:03.270
but I don't know, you've only
got some very small sample.

00:19:03.270 --> 00:19:06.100
But if this entire
room likes it,

00:19:06.100 --> 00:19:08.220
the chances of it being
good are even better.

00:19:08.220 --> 00:19:10.140
And so the more
diverse voices that you

00:19:10.140 --> 00:19:13.320
have weighing in on the type
of content that you're making,

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:16.390
the better chance you have
of that content being better.

00:19:17.165 --> 00:19:18.540
MARJAI ROBERTS:
Definitely agree.

00:19:18.540 --> 00:19:19.920
WILL PACKER: That was my
second best answer, guys.

