growing production
hubs in the US

00:20:24.220 --> 00:20:27.970
with all the tax incentives
in the state, what is it

00:20:27.970 --> 00:20:30.170
like producing in Atlanta?

00:20:30.170 --> 00:20:32.272
And how do you like it?

00:20:32.272 --> 00:20:33.480
WILL PACKER: Atlanta's great.

00:20:33.480 --> 00:20:36.910
It's obviously-- we're
here at a global company

00:20:36.910 --> 00:20:40.390
and the world now is
completely connected.

00:20:40.390 --> 00:20:43.490
And so no matter where
you produce the content--

00:20:43.490 --> 00:20:45.229
ultimately,
distribution has changed

00:20:45.229 --> 00:20:47.270
and no matter where you
are, where it's produced,

00:20:47.270 --> 00:20:49.260
you can get access to content.

00:20:49.260 --> 00:20:52.570
So a lot of times, the decisions
about where to make the content

00:20:52.570 --> 00:20:55.440
are driven by creative
and by fiscal.

00:20:55.440 --> 00:20:59.840
So ultimately, Atlanta's a great
market that's been very smart,

00:20:59.840 --> 00:21:02.400
the state of Georgia has put
text incentives in place.

00:21:02.400 --> 00:21:04.570
It was my home market
market even before those tax

00:21:04.570 --> 00:21:06.364
incentives were in
place, I like it

00:21:06.364 --> 00:21:08.030
because it has a lot
of different looks,

00:21:08.030 --> 00:21:10.270
so as a creative
person you can shoot

00:21:10.270 --> 00:21:13.912
something that can be very
metropolitan, also very rural.

00:21:13.912 --> 00:21:17.770
It's Southern, but yet because
it has so many transplants,

00:21:17.770 --> 00:21:22.970
it has a flavor that feels very
diverse, not just Southern.

00:21:22.970 --> 00:21:25.339
So I like it for
personal reasons

00:21:25.339 --> 00:21:26.880
because I like that
kind of diversity

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:30.550
and I like that kind of cultural
melting pot that Atlanta is.

00:21:30.550 --> 00:21:33.240
But for business
reasons, it is now

00:21:33.240 --> 00:21:37.880
at the forefront of one of the
most efficient places to shoot,

00:21:37.880 --> 00:21:41.250
and other studios and
producers are following suit.

00:21:41.250 --> 00:21:45.400
And that's how it works
in my business, where

00:21:45.400 --> 00:21:47.660
the tax incentives are-- you
build it, they will come.

00:21:47.660 --> 00:21:49.800
You put a tax incentive
in place, whoever's

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:53.370
got the highest percentage, you
will find your favorite shows

00:21:53.370 --> 00:21:56.370
and movies, and other content--
documentaries, whatever it is--

00:21:56.370 --> 00:21:58.590
being shot in those markets.

00:21:58.590 --> 00:22:01.490
MARJAI ROBERTS: I heard
in a BET Genius Talks

00:22:01.490 --> 00:22:04.870
interview you did with
Boris Kodjoe last year,

00:22:04.870 --> 00:22:08.572
you mentioned that if newcomers
want Hollywood to pay attention

00:22:08.572 --> 00:22:11.030
to them, they really have to
start making their own content

00:22:11.030 --> 00:22:15.260
and starting to make
money on that content.

00:22:15.260 --> 00:22:17.220
That reminded me a lot
of our YouTube creators

00:22:17.220 --> 00:22:20.620
and how they're using
limited resources to build up

00:22:20.620 --> 00:22:22.720
a subscribership and fan base.

00:22:22.720 --> 00:22:26.770
So how big do you
think technology

00:22:26.770 --> 00:22:30.690
has played in helping creators
get their work out there?

00:22:30.690 --> 00:22:35.609
And how different was that for
you when you first started?

00:22:35.609 --> 00:22:36.900
WILL PACKER: Technology's huge.

00:22:36.900 --> 00:22:40.610
Technology, it affects
everything that we do,

00:22:40.610 --> 00:22:44.370
but you can't overstate
the impact of technology

00:22:44.370 --> 00:22:46.220
on the film and
television business.

00:22:46.220 --> 00:22:49.280
So in every aspect
at every level--

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:53.650
I don't care if you're
talking about a $150 million

00:22:53.650 --> 00:22:57.780
tent pole production or a
$2 million indie-- the way

00:22:57.780 --> 00:23:02.610
that that content is created now
is affected by the technology

00:23:02.610 --> 00:23:04.280
level that we're at right now.

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:08.630
So for me, I love it
because what it has done

00:23:08.630 --> 00:23:11.970
is remove some of the
barriers that were there

00:23:11.970 --> 00:23:15.100
for young artists who want to
get into the movie business.

00:23:15.100 --> 00:23:17.640
Because now, when
I first started

00:23:17.640 --> 00:23:21.350
I had to shoot my
first film, on film.

00:23:21.350 --> 00:23:25.730
I had to go out and actually
buy celluloid to shoot my film,

00:23:25.730 --> 00:23:28.310
60 millimeters is what
we shot it on-- Super 16,

00:23:28.310 --> 00:23:30.700
actually, thank you very
much-- and we shot the film,

00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:32.200
and we had to edit
it, and we didn't

00:23:32.200 --> 00:23:34.790
have digital capabilities
at that time.

00:23:34.790 --> 00:23:38.080
Now, you can shoot a
movie, a complete movie,

00:23:38.080 --> 00:23:40.360
on your cell phone, on your
smartphone, absolutely.

00:23:40.360 --> 00:23:43.172
So on your Android
smartphone, by the way.

00:23:46.270 --> 00:23:49.350
I love that because
now you can go out

00:23:49.350 --> 00:23:52.770
and you don't have to go to
one of the gatekeepers to say,

00:23:52.770 --> 00:23:55.010
will you give me
a ton of resources

00:23:55.010 --> 00:23:56.470
in order to create my content.

00:23:56.470 --> 00:24:00.330
And if it's good enough, and
if people want to see it,

00:24:00.330 --> 00:24:03.651
and they will go and follow
you on YouTube and click it,

00:24:03.651 --> 00:24:06.150
and you have a bunch of views,
Hollywood will pay attention.

00:24:06.150 --> 00:24:08.900
Hollywood, by its very nature,
is a reactive industry.

00:24:08.900 --> 00:24:10.950
It's not very proactive,
unfortunately.

00:24:10.950 --> 00:24:12.040
It's reactive.

00:24:12.040 --> 00:24:15.300
And so you have an opportunity
to get Hollywood's attention

00:24:15.300 --> 00:24:16.810
because those
barriers aren't there.

00:24:16.810 --> 00:24:18.705
You can go out with
very limited resources,

00:24:18.705 --> 00:24:20.330
and if you're good,
if you're creative,

00:24:20.330 --> 00:24:22.746
if you how to market it, you
know how to find an audience,

00:24:22.746 --> 00:24:25.362
Hollywood will find you and
say, help us to exploit you.

00:24:25.362 --> 00:24:26.320
It's what they will do.

00:24:26.320 --> 00:24:28.450
But ultimately, it
gets your content out

00:24:28.450 --> 00:24:29.380
to a wider audience.

00:24:29.865 --> 00:24:30.990
MARJAI ROBERTS: Definitely.

00:24:30.990 --> 00:24:32.448
So you already gave
us a little bit

00:24:32.448 --> 00:24:34.030
of advice for
budding producers, do

00:24:34.030 --> 00:24:36.410
you have any other
words of encouragement

00:24:36.410 --> 00:24:38.279
for content creators
and producers

00:24:38.279 --> 00:24:39.570
out there trying to get their--

00:24:39.570 --> 00:24:40.820
WILL PACKER: Go out and do it.

00:24:40.820 --> 00:24:43.010
Go out-- and that's
my thing now, go out.

00:24:43.010 --> 00:24:44.920
Don't use the excuse
of, well, I haven't

00:24:44.920 --> 00:24:46.461
gotten to a particular
level, I don't

00:24:46.461 --> 00:24:49.270
have enough resources--
go out and do it.

00:24:49.270 --> 00:24:52.170
Inevitabily, the more you
do, the better you will get.

00:24:52.170 --> 00:24:55.402
And so what I always tell young
people interested in getting

00:24:55.402 --> 00:24:57.610
into the business is don't
wait for somebody like me,

00:24:57.610 --> 00:24:59.910
or anybody else, to come
and ordain you, and give you

00:24:59.910 --> 00:25:02.230
a shot, and say, here's
a big Hollywood budget.

00:25:02.230 --> 00:25:03.470
Just go out and do it.

00:25:03.470 --> 00:25:05.580
Go out and start shooting.

00:25:05.580 --> 00:25:07.670
Your first stuff is
probably going to be bad.

00:25:07.670 --> 00:25:09.290
That's OK, get that
out of your system

00:25:09.290 --> 00:25:11.072
and get to the good stuff.

00:25:11.072 --> 00:25:16.770
I think that because people
that are really ambitious

00:25:16.770 --> 00:25:18.360
and go getters, and
really passionate

00:25:18.360 --> 00:25:21.160
and driven about it, now because
there are so many avenues

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:23.180
to be able to create
your own stuff--

00:25:23.180 --> 00:25:26.330
and in distribution outlets,
there are more cable,

00:25:26.330 --> 00:25:28.770
and on demand outlets,
and digital outlets,

00:25:28.770 --> 00:25:33.040
and channels online to put your
content on and have it seen

00:25:33.040 --> 00:25:37.210
by a wide audience than there
ever were before-- so if you're

00:25:37.210 --> 00:25:39.930
hungry and you're really
serious about doing,

00:25:39.930 --> 00:25:42.000
there is an opportunity there.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.400
So now that the
excuses are removed,

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:47.020
you have a lot more people
that are creating content,

00:25:47.020 --> 00:25:48.872
so now the cream has
to rise to the top.

00:25:48.872 --> 00:25:51.330
You have to figure out how to
make your content good enough

00:25:51.330 --> 00:25:53.230
that people will notice
it because there's

00:25:53.230 --> 00:25:55.020
a lot of content out there.

00:25:55.020 --> 00:25:57.930
So now it challenges you as
a filmmaker, as an actor,

00:25:57.930 --> 00:26:00.449
as a writer, as a director,
to stand out and be better

00:26:00.449 --> 00:26:02.990
than some of the peers out there
that are just throwing stuff

00:26:02.990 --> 00:26:03.770
at the wall.

00:26:03.770 --> 00:26:05.207
MARJAI ROBERTS: Definitely.

00:26:05.207 --> 00:26:07.540
So we're going to start taking
a few audience questions,

00:26:07.540 --> 00:26:12.230
so you can definitely go and
line up in the middle there.

00:26:12.230 --> 00:26:15.790
But before that, I
wanted to ask you

00:26:15.790 --> 00:26:17.730
what inspired you to
get into filmmaking?

00:26:17.730 --> 00:26:20.260
I know some of you
may not know that you

00:26:20.260 --> 00:26:22.850
graduated from FAMU with an
electrical engineering degree--

00:26:22.850 --> 00:26:23.850
WILL PACKER: I did, yes.

00:26:23.850 --> 00:26:26.660
MARJAI ROBERTS: --so that
resonates here at Google.

00:26:26.660 --> 00:26:29.040
But how did you leap from
engineering to film ?

00:26:31.020 --> 00:26:35.625
WILL PACKER: I never had a
passion for engineering--

00:26:35.625 --> 00:26:40.060
no offense to present
company-- but for me, I

00:26:40.060 --> 00:26:43.230
was strong in technology,
and math, and science

00:26:43.230 --> 00:26:46.680
coming in to college and I got
a scholarship to pursue that.

00:26:46.680 --> 00:26:48.610
And there was a
push at that time,

00:26:48.610 --> 00:26:53.160
not unsimilar to how it is now,
to increase minority graduates

00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:54.710
in technical fields.

00:26:54.710 --> 00:26:57.610
And so I got a scholarship
that encouraged me to go into

00:26:57.610 --> 00:27:00.430
to get a degree in electrical
engineering, and along the way,

00:27:00.430 --> 00:27:02.990
I hooked up with a buddy,
a lifelong friend of mine

00:27:02.990 --> 00:27:05.610
named Rob Hardy, and he wanted
to be a director, that's

00:27:05.610 --> 00:27:06.560
all he wanted to do.

00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:08.390
He was like, I want to
be a movie director.

00:27:08.390 --> 00:27:09.806
That wasn't my
particular passion,

00:27:09.806 --> 00:27:11.580
but I wanted to be
an entrepreneur.

00:27:11.580 --> 00:27:14.910
And so I helped him to
make his first movie.

00:27:14.910 --> 00:27:20.730
And after we made it, I was able
to get distribution, hustle it

00:27:20.730 --> 00:27:23.360
into the theaters locally.

00:27:23.360 --> 00:27:25.930
Ultimately, I helped him
get the actor, the finance

00:27:25.930 --> 00:27:28.620
and the distribution,
and then do that again

00:27:28.620 --> 00:27:29.950
with another small project.

00:27:29.950 --> 00:27:32.234
And later I learned that's
what a producer basically

00:27:32.234 --> 00:27:34.650
does, you go and get financing
for projects and create it.

00:27:34.650 --> 00:27:37.160
So I stumbled into
being a movie producer,

00:27:37.160 --> 00:27:38.980
it wasn't something
that I checked a box

00:27:38.980 --> 00:27:40.521
when you're trying
to figure out what

00:27:40.521 --> 00:27:43.280
your career's going to be as
a teenager or college student.

00:27:43.280 --> 00:27:45.845
But we were able to
make it successful,

00:27:45.845 --> 00:27:48.350
we took a little small movie
and made a little bit of money,

00:27:48.350 --> 00:27:49.150
and I said, you know what?

00:27:49.150 --> 00:27:51.280
This is my entrepreneurial
endeavor right here,

00:27:51.280 --> 00:27:52.380
this is a business model.

00:27:52.380 --> 00:27:55.810
I'm going to go and I'm going
to do this movie producer thing.

00:27:55.810 --> 00:27:59.869
I learned on the job, never went
to film school, trial by fire,

00:27:59.869 --> 00:28:01.410
making a lot of
mistakes, doing a lot

00:28:01.410 --> 00:28:04.020
of things wrong, but
ultimately hustled until I

00:28:04.020 --> 00:28:07.010
got to the point where
my content actually was

00:28:07.010 --> 00:28:09.150
good enough for people to see.

00:28:09.150 --> 00:28:11.260
And a lot of people to
see it, at this point.

00:28:11.260 --> 00:28:11.900
MARJAI ROBERTS: Definitely.

00:28:11.900 --> 00:28:13.310
Congratulations on that success.

00:28:13.310 --> 00:28:14.268
WILL PACKER: Thank you.

00:28:14.268 --> 00:28:18.300
MARJAI ROBERTS: So what are
you most proud of of "Truth Be

00:28:18.300 --> 00:28:18.850
Told?"

00:28:18.850 --> 00:28:21.344
And I would love to learn
more about any future projects

00:28:21.344 --> 00:28:22.260
you're working on now.

00:28:22.260 --> 00:28:24.593
WILL PACKER: With "Truth Be
Told," I'm proud of the fact

00:28:24.593 --> 00:28:26.210
that its organically
diverse, it's

00:28:26.210 --> 00:28:28.400
not something that
is a show that's

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:29.540
diverse for diverse's sake.

00:28:29.540 --> 00:28:33.080
It's a show about real people,
and it pushes the envelope,

00:28:33.080 --> 00:28:36.970
it's provocative but
not in an offensive way.

00:28:36.970 --> 00:28:38.870
It's fun, it's light
and I like that.

00:28:38.870 --> 00:28:41.930
And I think that the timing
is right for that kind of show

00:28:41.930 --> 00:28:43.820
on television and I
think that audiences

00:28:43.820 --> 00:28:47.572
who tune in and watch it, will
fall in love these characters.

00:28:47.572 --> 00:28:49.572
I'm proud of that, I'm
proud to be a part of it.

00:28:49.572 --> 00:28:51.113
MARJAI ROBERTS:
Definitely, congrats.

00:28:51.113 --> 00:28:53.160
So we'll take a few
Q&amp;A from the audience.

00:28:53.840 --> 00:28:56.184
AUDIENCE: First, I would
like to say, welcome Rattler.

00:28:56.184 --> 00:28:56.850
WILL PACKER: Oh!

00:28:56.850 --> 00:28:57.350
Thank you.

00:28:57.350 --> 00:28:58.790
FAMU in the house.

00:28:58.790 --> 00:29:00.020
AUDIENCE: Also an EE.

00:29:00.020 --> 00:29:00.610
WILL PACKER: Love that.

00:29:00.610 --> 00:29:02.360
AUDIENCE: Probably the
same scholarship program

00:29:02.360 --> 00:29:03.850
and also not an
engineer anymore.

00:29:03.850 --> 00:29:05.530
WILL PACKER: I love it,
when did you come out?

00:29:05.530 --> 00:29:07.613
AUDIENCE: I came out in
2000, so my contemporaries

00:29:07.613 --> 00:29:10.002
would be people like John
Brown, Joe Carrol-- I

00:29:10.002 --> 00:29:12.460
was on Senate with him-- Reggie
Harris and that whole crew.

00:29:12.460 --> 00:29:13.459
WILL PACKER: Absolutely.

00:29:13.459 --> 00:29:14.540
Wow, what a small world.

00:29:14.540 --> 00:29:15.900
MARJAI ROBERTS: That's
actually a manager on my team.

00:29:15.900 --> 00:29:16.733
WILL PACKER: Really?

00:29:16.733 --> 00:29:17.347
I love it.

00:29:17.347 --> 00:29:19.430
AUDIENCE: So I've been
watch you work ever since--

00:29:19.430 --> 00:29:21.240
WILL PACKER: We should just
keep the "convo" between us,

00:29:21.240 --> 00:29:21.310
this is--

00:29:21.310 --> 00:29:22.050
AUDIENCE: Right, exactly.

00:29:22.050 --> 00:29:23.430
WILL PACKER: --completely
irreverent to everybody

00:29:23.430 --> 00:29:25.310
in the room, and
everybody has no idea

00:29:25.310 --> 00:29:27.196
what we're talking about,
but that's awesome.

00:29:27.196 --> 00:29:28.320
AUDIENCE: That'll be lunch.

00:29:28.320 --> 00:29:28.990
WILL PACKER: Yeah.

00:29:28.990 --> 00:29:31.573
AUDIENCE: So I've been watching
your work since Chocolate City

00:29:31.573 --> 00:29:33.940
at TOPS, Trois.

00:29:33.940 --> 00:29:36.299
Interested in-- I know the
journey that you've gone

00:29:36.299 --> 00:29:38.840
through and I've been watching
for probably, what is it now--

00:29:38.840 --> 00:29:40.350
WILL PACKER: Chocolate
City was my first movie,

00:29:40.350 --> 00:29:41.974
I know that you might
be a little lost.

00:29:41.974 --> 00:29:44.930
When I was a student
at FAMU, Florida A&amp;M,

00:29:44.930 --> 00:29:47.259
I did a little small, small,
movie, that $20,000 movie,

00:29:47.259 --> 00:29:48.550
and it's called Chocolate City.

00:29:48.550 --> 00:29:50.549
It was a movie about
college life as we knew it.

00:29:50.549 --> 00:29:53.090
Horrible little movie but it
started a pretty nice career.

00:29:53.090 --> 00:29:54.131
All right, where were we?

00:29:54.131 --> 00:29:56.610
AUDIENCE: And we all had
to watch in orientation.

00:29:56.610 --> 00:29:58.450
So on this journey,
I know there's

00:29:58.450 --> 00:30:01.210
a lot of personal development
behind the success

00:30:01.210 --> 00:30:03.720
that people see outwardly,
I'm interested in knowing

00:30:03.720 --> 00:30:07.020
what is probably some of the
biggest personal challenges

00:30:07.020 --> 00:30:09.210
that you've had to
grow through in order

00:30:09.210 --> 00:30:13.680
to be able to look at the
Will Packer that was then,

00:30:13.680 --> 00:30:15.460
to the person that
we see now before us?

00:30:15.460 --> 00:30:17.300
WILL PACKER: That's
an excellent question.

00:30:17.300 --> 00:30:20.040
For me, my personal
growth has all

00:30:20.040 --> 00:30:23.999
been around learning the
work-life balance because when

00:30:23.999 --> 00:30:26.290
I get the opportunity to come
and have talks like this,

00:30:26.290 --> 00:30:29.120
and talk to people, it is
always about the success

00:30:29.120 --> 00:30:32.170
that I've had as a film
producer or television producer,

00:30:32.170 --> 00:30:34.430
and the projects that I
have and what's coming up.

00:30:34.430 --> 00:30:37.170
But what really, really
defines me is family

00:30:37.170 --> 00:30:39.520
because if you ask
me who I am, I'm

00:30:39.520 --> 00:30:43.100
going to say I'm a father and a
husband first who also happens

00:30:43.100 --> 00:30:44.640
to work in Hollywood.

00:30:44.640 --> 00:30:47.490
So for me, that balance--
my foundation is very strong

00:30:47.490 --> 00:30:49.840
and allows me to go out
and do the work that I

00:30:49.840 --> 00:30:52.850
do in a very, very
challenging, competitive field

00:30:52.850 --> 00:30:55.000
because I've got that
great family foundation.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:57.530
And so as I have
grown personally,

00:30:57.530 --> 00:30:59.940
the maturity to really
understand and grasp

00:30:59.940 --> 00:31:04.200
that work-life balance
has been immense in terms

00:31:04.200 --> 00:31:06.520
of giving me a leg up,
even on some of my peers

00:31:06.520 --> 00:31:07.370
who don't have that.

00:31:09.974 --> 00:31:12.390
AUDIENCE: First, thank you for
spending some time with us,

00:31:12.390 --> 00:31:13.349
know you're very busy--

00:31:13.349 --> 00:31:15.889
WILL PACKER: I thought you're
going to say you were from FAMU

00:31:15.889 --> 00:31:17.600
and I was going to
say, this is a setup,

00:31:17.600 --> 00:31:19.090
this whole room is fake.

00:31:19.090 --> 00:31:21.430
None of you people work
at Google, what is this?

00:31:21.430 --> 00:31:22.460
Is this an intervention?

00:31:22.460 --> 00:31:23.360
What's going on?

00:31:23.360 --> 00:31:23.910
No.

00:31:23.910 --> 00:31:24.480
AUDIENCE: Not quite.

00:31:24.480 --> 00:31:27.021
But I was wondering if you could
talk a little bit about what

00:31:27.021 --> 00:31:31.000
pressure, if any you feel, as
one of a handful of producers

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:34.060
that can push content through
the Hollywood machine featuring

00:31:34.060 --> 00:31:36.880
predominantly African-American
actors or themes.

00:31:36.880 --> 00:31:38.500
I know the two aren't
always the same,

00:31:38.500 --> 00:31:40.507
but what pressure,
if any, you feel?

00:31:40.507 --> 00:31:42.090
I wonder if you could
talk about that?

00:31:42.830 --> 00:31:44.830
WILL PACKER: First of
all, when you say handful,

00:31:44.830 --> 00:31:47.780
it's a small hand, I'm
going to be honest with you.

00:31:47.780 --> 00:31:50.900
There are not many
African-American producers

00:31:50.900 --> 00:31:53.310
that are fortunate enough
to produce on the level

00:31:53.310 --> 00:31:55.860
that I have been fortunate
enough to produce on.

00:31:55.860 --> 00:32:00.290
I see it as an opportunity
because right now I

00:32:00.290 --> 00:32:03.280
am one of very few
voices, so I always

00:32:03.280 --> 00:32:07.360
want to be the
person-- the parable is

00:32:07.360 --> 00:32:11.770
the shoe salesman who goes
into the land of no shoes.

00:32:11.770 --> 00:32:13.820
It's-- I don't know,
people look at me crazy.

00:32:13.820 --> 00:32:16.700
So this story is that there
were two shoe salesmen,

00:32:16.700 --> 00:32:19.800
and one went to
this far away town

00:32:19.800 --> 00:32:23.130
and came back to the
shoe company and said,

00:32:23.130 --> 00:32:25.830
oh this is horrible, we
can go into this town.

00:32:25.830 --> 00:32:29.200
They don't know what a shoe is,
they don't wear shoes, move on.

00:32:29.200 --> 00:32:31.890
And then the second salesman
went to the same town

00:32:31.890 --> 00:32:34.440
and came back and said, oh
my god, this is perfect.

00:32:34.440 --> 00:32:36.080
Unlimited potential for growth.

00:32:36.080 --> 00:32:39.442
We can take it over and start
our whole marketing machine

00:32:39.442 --> 00:32:41.150
here, and so he saw
an opportunity there.

00:32:41.150 --> 00:32:44.240
So for me, I see an
opportunity if I'm

00:32:44.240 --> 00:32:46.210
the only one in the
room that's doing

00:32:46.210 --> 00:32:48.570
a particular type of content.

00:32:48.570 --> 00:32:50.100
But I know that's
going to change,

00:32:50.100 --> 00:32:51.640
and I know that if
I do it well, it

00:32:51.640 --> 00:32:53.681
would open the door--
because, as I said earlier,

00:32:53.681 --> 00:32:56.200
Hollywood is reactive--
and so you will have people

00:32:56.200 --> 00:33:00.000
that will say, give me more of
insert successful content here.

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:03.720
Give me more movies and
TV shows like insert

00:33:03.720 --> 00:33:06.370
successful producers'
content there.

00:33:06.370 --> 00:33:08.970
So for me I see it as a
responsibility, but also

00:33:08.970 --> 00:33:10.090
an opportunity.

00:33:10.090 --> 00:33:13.900
And I know it will
change, it will.

00:33:13.900 --> 00:33:16.060
Right now I'm definitely
enjoying the ride

00:33:16.060 --> 00:33:19.220
because it allows
me to take risks

00:33:19.220 --> 00:33:22.840
because the expectations
are still not

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:27.334
extremely high for
content that is diverse.

00:33:27.334 --> 00:33:29.500
It's changing though, it's
changing because you look

00:33:29.500 --> 00:33:32.130
at the top shows on television
and the top movies in theaters

00:33:32.130 --> 00:33:35.200
for the last-- there
was a run of five weeks,

00:33:35.200 --> 00:33:38.130
it started with "Straight Outta
Compton," where the number one

00:33:38.130 --> 00:33:43.600
movie in the country featured
African-American leads for five

00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:44.490
weeks in a row.

00:33:44.490 --> 00:33:47.300
And then, of course, the number
one show on television right

00:33:47.300 --> 00:33:49.620
now is "Empire," so
it says something

00:33:49.620 --> 00:33:53.680
about the-- and those aren't
just black audiences that

00:33:53.680 --> 00:33:57.990
are watching those shows-- so
it says something about where

00:33:57.990 --> 00:34:00.360
the country is in terms
of the type of content

00:34:00.360 --> 00:34:02.037
they're willing to embrace.

00:34:02.037 --> 00:34:02.870
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:34:04.140 --> 00:34:05.310
MARJAI ROBERTS: Thanks guys.

00:34:05.310 --> 00:34:07.260
So one question I did
want to ask about,

00:34:07.260 --> 00:34:10.300
that I'm excited about,
is you are producing

00:34:10.300 --> 00:34:13.380
the remake of "Roots" and
I'm hearing about "Uncle

00:34:13.380 --> 00:34:16.800
Buck," which was a remake.

00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:19.989
Mike Epps is playing
it, originally--

00:34:19.989 --> 00:34:20.989
WILL PACKER: John Candy.

00:34:20.989 --> 00:34:22.198
MARJAI ROBERTS: --John Candy.

00:34:22.198 --> 00:34:24.572
So I'm excited about those,
can you tell us a little bit,

00:34:24.572 --> 00:34:25.870
sneak peak about that or--

00:34:25.870 --> 00:34:27.380
WILL PACKER: Sure, yeah.

00:34:27.380 --> 00:34:29.139
Two very different
projects, obviously,

00:34:29.139 --> 00:34:30.780
"Uncle Buck" and "Roots."

00:34:30.780 --> 00:34:35.670
So I don't see a mash
up coming any time soon.

00:34:35.670 --> 00:34:37.110
MARJAI ROBERTS: Not at all.

00:34:37.110 --> 00:34:39.400
WILL PACKER: "Uncle Buck"
is an interesting project

00:34:39.400 --> 00:34:43.639
because it is revered
in a lot of circles.

00:34:43.639 --> 00:34:46.000
The great John Candy,
it's a cult classic,

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:49.080
nobody will ever be John Candy
and we didn't approach it

00:34:49.080 --> 00:34:51.690
with an eye towards
replacing John Candy

00:34:51.690 --> 00:34:56.139
or doing the same show, the
same movie, as a TV show.

00:34:56.139 --> 00:34:59.280
We looked at the theme, the
heart of what that was about,

00:34:59.280 --> 00:35:00.510
and we made it our own.

00:35:00.510 --> 00:35:03.310
And so we've got an
amazing team of creators

00:35:03.310 --> 00:35:05.830
that have put a show together
around the super talented

00:35:05.830 --> 00:35:10.310
comedian, Mike Epps, and it
follows that same formula

00:35:10.310 --> 00:35:13.374
that was in "Uncle Buck," but
it's a very different show.

00:35:13.374 --> 00:35:15.540
And it's something I'm
excited about because I think

00:35:15.540 --> 00:35:17.998
it's a type of show that will
resonate with audiences today

00:35:17.998 --> 00:35:20.541
because it's real.

00:35:20.541 --> 00:35:23.570
Families today are not just
the traditional families

00:35:23.570 --> 00:35:25.910
of '80s television, they
look a lot different,

00:35:25.910 --> 00:35:28.390
and this is a family that
looks a lot different.

00:35:28.390 --> 00:35:31.150
And then with "Roots,"
that is something that I'm

00:35:31.150 --> 00:35:32.450
really, really proud of.

00:35:32.450 --> 00:35:33.686
I'm proud to be a part of it.

00:35:33.686 --> 00:35:35.310
It's obviously a
tremendous undertaking

00:35:35.310 --> 00:35:38.560
that I don't take
lightly, remaking

00:35:38.560 --> 00:35:41.790
an iconic classic, the
most watched television

00:35:41.790 --> 00:35:45.020
series in television history.

00:35:45.020 --> 00:35:47.720
It is something that
I'm doing because I

00:35:47.720 --> 00:35:50.040
know there's an entire
generation of youth that

00:35:50.040 --> 00:35:54.010
have not seen it and it deserves
a contemporary retelling.

00:35:54.010 --> 00:35:56.260
So we've got an amazing
team, amazing actors,

00:35:56.260 --> 00:35:58.700
amazing directors and I'm
happy to be a part of it.

00:35:58.700 --> 00:36:01.200
MARJAI ROBERTS: Great,
we're looking forward to it.

